<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-097-035 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 996 678</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  August 1991 v9 n8 p223(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The art of persuasion. (creating color presentations) (in How Tosection, includes related articles on chart redraws in Freelanceand color transparencies) (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jantz, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Color adds interest to presentations, but a poor choice of colorsor color schemes is worse than no color at all.andP;  Some presentationsoftware packages offer pre-designed color schemes with colorsthat mix harmoniously in the backgrounds, text, borders and bargraphs, but they do not guide users in choosing the best schemefor the particular presentation.andP;  Users should choose colors thatinteract well with corporate logos, that match the medium in whichthe presentation will be given and reflect the mood of thepresentation.andP;  Cool colors are best for business discussions, warmcolors are best for product introductions.andP;  The color schemeshould be consistent throughout the presentation, and no more thanfour or five colors should be used.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialColorPresentation SoftwarePresentations.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Color wheels are useful for choosing colors that do not clash.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>